      c = (year -1) // 100 +1        # compute suffix        if 11 <= (c % 100) <= 13:            suffix = 'th'        else:            last_digit = c %10            if last_digit ==1:                suffix = 'st'            elif last_digit ==2:                suffix = 'nd'            elif last_digit ==3:                suffix = 'rd'            else:                suffix = 'th'        key = f\\"{c}{suffix} Century\\"        # add to result        if key not in result:            result[key] = []        result[key].append(event)    return resultWait, but wait: in the sample input, the events are ordered, but in the output, the events are in the order they were added. So the function should preserve the order of events within each century.Yes, because for each event, it appends to the list in the order they are processed.Testing with the sample input:events = [    (\\"French Revolution\\", 1789),    (\\"American Civil War\\", 1861),    (\\"World War I\\", 1914),    (\\"World War II\\", 1939),    (\\"Moon Landing\\", 1969),    (\\"Fall of the Berlin Wall\\", 1989),    (\\"9/11 Attacks\\", 2001)]For each event:1. French Revolution, 1789 â†’ c = (1789-1)//100 +1 â†’ 1788//100=17 +1=18 â†’ 18th.2. American Civil War, 1861 â†’ (1861-1)=1860//100=18 +1=19 â†’ 19th.3. World War I, 1914 â†’ (1914-1)=1913//100=19 +1=20 â†’ 20th.4. World War II, 1939 â†’ same as above.5. Moon Landing, 1969 â†’ same.6. Berlin Wall, 1989 â†’ same.7. 9/11, 2001 â†’ (2001-1)=2000//100=20 +1=21 â†’ 21st.So the keys are 18th, 19th, 20th, 21st.The output dictionary will have these keys, and the events are added in the order they appear.So the sample output is as expected.What about edge cases?Test case 1: year 1 â†’ c = (1-1)//100 +1 = 0 +1=1 â†’ 1st Century.Test case 2: year 100 â†’ (100-1)=99//100=0 +1=1 â†’ 1st Century.Year 101 â†’ (101-1)=100//100=1 +1=2 â†’ 2nd Century.Year 999 â†’ (999-1)=998//100=9 +1=10 â†’ 10th Century.Year 1000 â†’ (1000-1)=999//100=9 +1=10 â†’ 10th Century.Year 1001 â†’ (1001-1)=1000//100=10 +1=11 â†’ 11th Century.Another test case: year 2000 â†’ (2000-1)=1999//100=19 +1=20 â†’ 20th Century.Year 2001 â†’ (2001-1)=2000//100=20 +1=21 â†’ 21st Century.So the function correctly handles these.Another test case: year 1120 â†’ (1120-1)=1119//100=11 +1=12 â†’ 12th Century.Another test case: year 113 â†’ (113-1)=112//100=1 +1=2 â†’ 2nd Century.Wait, no: 113 is in the 2nd century? Wait, 1-100 is 1st, 101-200 is 2nd. So 113 is in 2nd century. Correct.Another test case: year 11 â†’ (11-1)=10//100=0 +1=1 â†’ 1st Century.Year 12 â†’ same as above.Year 13 â†’ same.Year 21 â†’ (21-1)=20//100=0 +1=1 â†’ 1st Century.Wait, no. Wait, 21 is in the 1st century (1-100). So correct.Wait, but 21 is in the 1st century, but the suffix is 'st' because c=1.Yes, the key would be \\"1st Century\\".So the function should handle all these cases.Another edge case: year 0. Wait, but in the problem statement, the input is a list of events, and years are positive integers, I suppose. So perhaps we don't need to handle year 0 or negative years. But the function as written will handle it, but perhaps the problem expects only positive years.So, the function should be correct.Now, let's implement this.Wait, but in the code, I have to compute the suffix for each c. So the helper function is inside the loop.Alternatively, I could write a helper function, but for the sake of code brevity, it's fine to compute it inline.So, the code is as outlined above.Testing the sample input:events = [    (\\"French Revolution\\", 1789),    (\\"American Civil War\\", 1861),    (\\"World War I\\", 1914),    (\\"World War II\\", 1939),    (\\"Moon Landing\\", 1969),    (\\"Fall of the Berlin Wall\\", 1989),    (\\"9/11 Attacks\\", 2001)]The function should return the expected dictionary.Another test case: event in 1900 â†’ (1900-1)=1899//100=18 +1=19 â†’ 19th Century.Event in 1901 â†’ (1901-1)=1900//100=19 +1=20 â†’ 20th Century.So, the function correctly assigns 1900 to 19th and 1901 to 20th.